    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>S-curved legs with thin ankles which broaden to a shaped foot not unlike the head of a snake; used on tripod tables from the early 18th century.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000031831/Pain, Heritage of Country Furniture (1978)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>S-vormige poten met dunne enkels die breed uitlopen in een gevormde voet die op een slangekop lijkt. Wordt gebruikt op driepotige tafels uit de vroege 18e eeuw.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>S形腿腳造型，踝部細小，至腳座部分變寬，狀似蛇頭；用於西元十八世紀早期的三腳桌上。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
